            Nonetheless, presidential
policy does affect the health of the economy. Though the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fed</ENAMEX> is supposed to be
insulated from politics, it is not completely immune. A <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">four-year</TIMEX> term
alternating with the presidential-election cycle means that a one-term
<ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">president</ENAMEX> gets a <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Fed</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">chairman</ENAMEX> of his choosing for <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">just under 50 percent</NUMEX> of his
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">presidency</ENAMEX>, while a two-term <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">president</ENAMEX> has his own <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">appointee</ENAMEX> in control nearly
<NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">75 percent</NUMEX> of the time. A successful <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">chairman</ENAMEX> reflects well on the president
